With a third presidential candidate assassinated, Columbia's
government refused to put off the 1990 election and vowed to keep up
the fight against drug traffickers.  The Medellin drug cartel denied
responsibility for the assassination of presidential candidate Carlos
Pizarro, who died in a hail of bullets Thursday aboard a Colombian
jetliner.  On the same day, a man called the national radio network
station and detailed how the cartel allegedly ordered the killing.
When a candidate was killed in August, the government launched a
US-backed crackdown on Colombia's cocaine cartels.  Since then, drug
traffickers have killed more than 230 people.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d37"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900428-0108"
SELECTOR="G"
SUMMARIZER="G">   

Less than a month before the 1990 elections, a third presidential
candidate in Colombia, Carlos Pizarro, was assassinated in a jetliner
taking off from Bogota by a gunman on a suicide mission.  Pizarro's
bodyguards killed the assassin.  The assassination of the other two
candidates was blamed on drug traffickers.  The media, citing security
sources, reported that traffickers were the main suspects in Pizarro's
killing as well.  The Medallion cartel denied involvement.
Traffickers have killed nearly 300 Colombians in the past nine months
in an effort to halt the government's campaign to capture and expedite
drug barons to the United States.</SUM>

